<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="221" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[160,1156,142,307]" box="[160,262,142,168]" pageId="31" pageNumber="221">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,262,142,168]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="221">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[160,1156,142,307]" pageId="31" pageNumber="221">
Males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Costa &amp; Duarte &amp; Iannuzzi &amp; Grossi" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Costa &amp; Duarte &amp; Iannuzzi &amp; Grossi" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[262,408,178,203]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Strategus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="waldenfelsi" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[262,408,178,203]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="221">T. waldenfelsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[416,542,178,203]" pageId="31" pageNumber="221" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
have allometric development evidenced by the shape of male horn sometimes broader dorsoventrally at middle wider than basis in lateral view; longer (covering the head in dorsal view, surpassing the anterior margin of clypeus in lateral view) or shorter (not covering the head in dorsal view).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
